215","1244":"1244","9 July 1271":"9. juli 1271","Carew Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Hockering, Norfolk, England":"Hockering, Norfolk, England","Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"nl":{"about 1215–9 July 1271":"circa 1215–9 juli 1271","1215–1278":"1215–1278","1240–1297":"1240–1297","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1244–1297":"1244–1297","1215–1271":"1215–1271","1242":"1242","1286":"1286","1297":"1297","1240":"1240","1271":"1271","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","about 1215":"circa 1215","1244":"1244","9 July 1271":"9 juli 1271","Carew Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Hockering, Norfolk, England":"Hockering, Norfolk, England","Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1215–9 July 1271":"about 1215–9 July 1271","1215–1278":"1215–1278","1240–1297":"1240–1297","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1244–1297":"1244–1297","1215–1271":"1215–1271","1242":"1242","1286":"1286","1297":"1297","1240":"1240","1271":"1271","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","about 1215":"about 1215","1244":"1244","9 July 1271":"9 July 1271","Carew Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Hockering, Norfolk, England":"Hockering, Norfolk, England","Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marshall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: usually an occupational name ‘farrier’, occasionally a status name ‘chief official of a royal household or court; a high officer of state’, from Middle English <i>mareshal</i> and Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>. An even wider range of meanings is found in some other languages: compare for example Polish <b>Marszałek</b> (see   Marszalek  ). This name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century. It is also borne by Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Marschall  .","Americanized form of French   Mercier  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marchel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jacek, Ryszard.  German Ernst.","Polish: probably from French <i>maréchal</i> or Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>, which was originally an occupational name for someone who was in charge of the horses of a household, later a military rank for a senior general. See   Marshall   and compare   Marszalek  ."]},{"name":"Mercier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Gaston, Lucien, Aurele, Jacques, Normand, Laurent, Michel, Valmont.","French and Channel Islands (Jersey): occupational name for a merchant, from Old French <i>mercier</i>, from Late Latin <i>merciarius</i> (an agent derivative of <i>merx</i>, genitive <i>mercis</i> ‘merchandise’). This name was also taken to England by Huguenot refugees. Compare   Marshall   and   Mercy  ."]},{"name":"Maniscalco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Vito, Sal, Antonio, Ignazio, Carmelo, Francesco, Gaspare, Saverio, Antonino, Carlo, Damiano.","Italian (southern): occupational name from <i>maniscalco</i> ‘farrier’, altered from <i>marescalco</i> by folk etymology, probably influenced by <i>mano</i> ‘hand’, from medieval Latin <i>mariscalcus</i>, <i>marescalcus</i>. Compare   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marchal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gilles, Jacques, Maryse, Philippe, Pierre, Veronique.","French and Walloon: status name or occupational name from Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i> ‘marshal’. The term is of ancient Germanic origin (from <i>marah</i> ‘horse, mare’ + <i>scalc</i> ‘servant’) and was originally applied to a man who looked after horses. In the Middle Ages it also came to be used on the one hand as an occupational name for a farrier, and on the other as a status name for an officer of state, in particular a member of a royal household with military responsibilities. Compare English   Marshall   and 2 below.","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland, and is found mainly in Glamorgan, Wales."]},{"name":"Maskell","meanings":["English: variant of   Marshall  , derived from Middle English, Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i> ‘marshal’. The first element in the placename Mascallsbury (Essex) derives from the surname of a 13th-century individual named Robert <i>le Marescal</i>."]},{"name":"Marszalek","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Piotr, Alicja, Andrzej, Eugeniusz, Henryk, Jerzy, Kazimierz, Mieczyslaw, Wieslaw, Zbigniew, Zofia, Zygmunt.","Polish (<b>Marszałek</b>): occupational or status name from the vocabulary word <i>marszałek</i> ‘marshal’, denoting anything from a high court official, a field marshal, or the chairman of the Polish parliament, to the senior servant in a great household. Compare English   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marshell","meanings":["English: variant of   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marschall","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Hedwig, Juergen, Reinhard, Theresia, Wilfried.","German: occupational name for a man in the service of a member of the nobility, originally one who looked after the horses, Middle High German <i>marschalc</i> (from <i>mar(c)</i> ‘noble horse’ + <i>schalk</i> ‘servant’). In time the term came to be used for a military rank or a certain court official. Compare   Marshall  .","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marshal","meanings":["(1997: 186;2007: 634; 2010: NA)","English and Scottish: variant of   Marshall  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":0,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":9,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":44,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Marshall was born about 1215, in Hockering, Norfolk, England. She married William Carew in 1238, in Pembrokeshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died on 9 July 1271, in Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 57."},"et":{"about 1215–9 July 1271":"umbes 1215–9. juuli 1271","1215–1278":"1215–1278","1240–1297":"1240–1297","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1244–1297":"1244–1297","1215–1271":"1215–1271","1242":"1242","1286":"1286","1297":"1297","1240":"1240","1271":"1271","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","about 1215":"umbes 1215","1244":"1244","9 July 1271":"9. juuli 1271","Carew Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Hockering, Norfolk, England":"Hockering, Norfolk, England","Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1215–9 July 1271":"noin 1215–9. heinäkuuta 1271","1215–1278":"1215–1278","1240–1297":"1240–1297","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1244–1297":"1244–1297","1215–1271":"1215–1271","1242":"1242","1286":"1286","1297":"1297","1240":"1240","1271":"1271","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","about 1215":"noin 1215","1244":"1244","9 July 1271":"9. heinäkuuta 1271","Carew Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Hockering, Norfolk, England":"Hockering, Norfolk, England","Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1215–9 July 1271":"environ 1215–9 juillet 1271","1215–1278":"1215–1278","1240–1297":"1240–1297","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1244–1297":"1244–1297","1215–1271":"1215–1271","1242":"1242","1286":"1286","1297":"1297","1240":"1240","1271":"1271","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","about 1215":"environ 1215","1244":"1244","9